08102nam a22008535i 9780773563568DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735635687 a10.1515/97807735635682doi  a(DE-B1597)655731  a(OCoLC)732601021  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHC115 ǂb H53 1996eb 7aSCI0300002bisacsh04a330.971/06481 aBritton, John N.H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanada and the Global Economy :bThe Geography of Structural and Technological Change /cJohn N.H. Britton. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (472 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCanadian Association of Geographers Series in Canadian Geography ;v300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tForeign Trade in Goods and Services -- tExternal Shocks: Regional Implications of an Open Staple Economy -- tShifts in Canadian Direct Investment Abroad and Foreign Direct Investment in Canada -- tThe Canadian Financial System in International Perspective -- tTechnological Imperatives in Resource Sectors: Forest Products -- tRestructuring in the Canadian Mining and Mineral-Processing Industries -- tRedrawing the Canadian Energy Map -- tAgriculture in a World of Subsidies -- tEmployment Creation by Small Firms -- tOrganizational Restructuring of U. S.-based Manufacturing Subsidiaries and Plant Closure -- tRestructuring in Mature Manufacturing Industries: The Case of Canadian Clothing -- tRestructuring in a Continental Production System -- tHigh-Tech Canada -- tCapital, Technological Change, and Regional Growth -- tThe Role of Transportation in the Canadian Economy -- tThe Canadian Market and Activities Oriented to Consumers -- tThe Role and Location of Service Activities in the Canadian Space Economy -- tQuaternary Places in Canada -- tCanada’s Public Space Economy -- tSocio-spatial Restructuring of Canadian Labour Markets -- tTechnological Change and Innovation: Policy Issues -- tConclusion: Canada’s Emerging Economic Geography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors explore four central themes: the locational impacts of the openness of the Canadian economy, Canada's relatively simple economic geography in terms of regional variations in resources and urban development, the problems of keeping pace with rapid advances in technology, and the role of government in maintaining a national market and assisting economic development. They outline the essential elements of Canada's contemporary economic geography, highlight the origins and spatial imprint of change in the Canadian economy, and provide an assessment of Canada's participation in significant international patterns of economic change. Canada and the Global Economy is concerned not only with the economic size and location of consumption and production but also with institutional changes and shifts in employment, the sectoral composition of economic activity, and the organizational structure and locational behaviour of particular industries and firms. Special attention is given to the technological development of both established industries and new service and manufacturing activities. A timely addition to the field, it provides a geographic perspective on significant changes in jobs and types of work that result from the transformation of economic activities. Contributors: Trevor J. Barnes (UBC), John N.H. Britton (Toronto), James B. Cannon (Queen's), William J. Coffey (Montréal), J. Tait Davis (York), Geoffrey Dobilas (Toronto), William C. Found (York), Meric S. Gertler (Toronto), James M. Gilmour (consultant, Ottawa), Roger Hayter (Simon Fraser), John Holmes (Queen's), Anthony C. Lea (Compusearch, Toronto), Ian MacLachlan (Lethbridg